    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Margins of Spanglish</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Edward R Ward letter supports Roberto Gonzalez Echevarria March 28 Op-Ed article contending that 'Spanglish' indicates marginalization, not enfranchisement</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Roberto Gonzalez Echevarria (''Is 'Spanglish' a Language?'', Op-Ed, March 28) makes a subtle but vital point for his readers: ''Spanglish . . . indicates marginalization, not enfranchisement.'' He is correct.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Roberto Gonzalez Echevarria (''Is 'Spanglish' a Language?'', Op-Ed, March 28) makes a subtle but vital point for his readers: ''Spanglish . . . indicates marginalization, not enfranchisement.'' He is correct.</p>
        <p>Further, Mr. Echevarria might have added a second point: Those who defend the margins should realize that they must live in those margins. Are the backers of Spanglish (and ebonics?) so inclined? They should be ready for a rough and lonely ride.</p>
        <p>EDWARD R. WARD  Bogota, N.J., March 28, 1997</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
